Flour Mills of Nigeria Plc has shortlisted five finalists from category one of its FMN Prize for Innovation. The company said several small and medium enterprises submitted entries that had to do with solar-powered storage systems, hydroponic farming solutions, bio-recycling plants, and newer methods of generating electricity from food waste. According to a statement, the five finalists are Samson Ogbole (Ogun State), Amadi Ann Obianuju (Kogi State), Olarewaju Olufemi (Oyo State), Emmanuel Eze (Enugu State), and Chuks Ogbonna (Rivers State). Flour Mills said, “After the rigorous screening process, the five finalists will now advance to the competition’s final stage – live pitch event to be held in Lagos. “The finalist will be adjudged by a panel of notable experts in the food industry including, Adenike Adeyemi (Chief Executive Officer, FATE Foundation), Mezuo Nwuneli (Managing Partner Sahel Capital Agribusiness Managers Ltd.), Mira Mehta (Founder and CEO of Tomato Jos Farming and Processing Limited), and Sadiq Usman (Director – Group Strategy and Stakeholder Relations at Flour Mills of Nigeria).” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com